author: @Sam-Magic
content: My analysis from the Flight-Radar APPS is as follow:On Jun 12, AI171 turned right at the T-Junction half-way of the runway instead of turning left to the end and then did U-turn before take-off.  (An hour before that, a Singapore Airline A350 did a U-turn first.) üò°Incidentally the day before, the Pilot's father was in Intensive Care and he promised his Dad that he would quit his job ASAP in order to look after him.  One can deduce that he is NOT in his normal state of mind.  Psychologically, he wanted to finish his last piloting job quickly and therefore took a short-cut. Unfortunately, with less speed after take-off, the plane STALLED (Momentum= Mass x Speed**2) üò≠I am writing this script with a mixed feeling as today is our Father's Day.  üò∞-- Prof. Sam HO, Research Fellow, Dept. of E

author: @kristinavb4398
content: The cause of the accident is a human factor: the pilot should have retracted the wheels at 600ft and wings should have remained. Instead,  the pilot "cleaned" the wings, but the wheels remained, which is an additional violation of the plane's aerodynamics and lift force. It was all at a low altitude, and there was no time for the pilot to fix his mistake. When the aircraft starts to sink, it needs a lot of height below so that the pilot can react and correct the error.

author: @KrishnanSubramanian-wt4gv
content:
Reasons could be ---
Before take off pilots have to check all take off procedures that includes FLAPS , Landing gear position indications, throttle position, cabin air pressure , wheel brake pressure , engine oil pressure, fuel pump conditions , stabilizers, rudder and aileron movements, thrust reversers in retracted position etc ! One of these check is FLAP !  if the FLAP position lever is in Forward position that will be the indication of FLAPS are not opened for take off ! If FLAPS are not DOWN at 15 or 25 degree deflection, plane can not take off even at 200 kph runway speed ! During take off checks before increasing throttle and rekeasing brakes , pilots might have ignored FLAPS lever postion for TAKE OFF slot at 25 degree because two boeing  crash incidents proved before !! Another reason if Thrust reversers deployed bymistake or system interlock fails that opens thrust reverser during take off speed also cause the engine to surge and lose power to lift off ! 3rd is if fuel line is clogged inside the engine combustion chamber also can be the main cause to lose engine power !!

author: @Sultan-vz9ty
content: Here is an expected analysis that must be considered and action must be taken to request the government to disclose the entire cockpit recording and the data recorder as well, otherwise the consequences will be dire for aviation safety and security around the world for everyone, not to mention the reputation and experience of the pilots from India, the Indian airline operator and its representatives. This is first. Secondly, regarding your question, and here is the most important point, I expect that such aircraft have an alarm system for such a reason as cutting off fuel to the engine during flight, and if it does not exist, this is a disaster. If it exists and does not activate or operate during the moment of fuel cut, this means that there is no electrical system that failed to issue an alarm, and a malfunction occurred in the system, which consequently prevented the issuance of the alarm in the cockpit. The malfunction may be a malfunction of one engine at the beginning and the other a little later. The turbofans then activate the RAT, which generated electricity for moments, enabling the distress call, which is a heroic act carried out by the pilots in my opinion. Here, it is necessary to focus and examine the timing and the time difference in milliseconds or seconds when exactly it was activated. These are the most important points that must be verified and their accuracy with the recordings, as the situation requires a quick reaction from the pilots to restore  Starting the engines is like restarting the engines after confirming the malfunction that may have occurred during takeoff. In my opinion, the pilots are heroes in what they did in trying to regain control of the plane in these exceptional circumstances, trying hard for the safety of those in the plane and those on the ground. Do not stop searching no matter the cost. You are experts in a time when the rabble and those with interests have increased at the expense of productive and hard-working minds. Good luck to all of you, and the whole truth will appear with your presence. Excuse me if there are any spelling errors. For your information, I am not a captain, but what matters to us is the truth, the future, and the safety of all.

author: @saramuthu6690
content:
Still to be verified but it looks like a catastrophic electrical failure on rotation. 




Flight: AI-171 | Aircraft: Boeing 787-8 | Date: June 25, 2025 | Route: Ahmedabad (VAAH) ‚Üí London Heathrow (EGLL)
Crash Site: ~1.2 km from VAAH Runway 23, post-V1 and rotation
Fatalities: 247 (243 onboard + 4 ground)
Survivors: 0 onboard survivors (alternate to original), 3 injured on ground

‚∏ª

üõ†Ô∏è  AAIB Preliminary Report Highlights

1. Primary Cause ‚Äì Electrical Power Transfer Interruption (PTI) During Rotation
	‚Ä¢	During transition from ground to airborne electrical configuration, the aircraft experienced a cascading dual-engine FADEC (Full Authority Digital Engine Control) failure.
	‚Ä¢	Root cause: Uncommanded bus transfer failure due to arcing in the main power relay box (PRB-A), traced to water ingress during pre-flight GPU disconnection in heavy rain.
	‚Ä¢	This led to loss of electronic engine control at rotation, resulting in both GEnx engines rolling back to ground idle within 4‚Äì5 seconds.

2. Flight Data Record Timeline
	‚Ä¢	+0:11 sec: Nose gear lifts off.
	‚Ä¢	+0:13 sec: Sudden engine rollback begins. Thrust reduces from 92% N1 to <27% within 3 seconds.
	‚Ä¢	+0:16 sec: Master caution + ENG FAIL L/R warnings. FO calls, ‚ÄúBoth engines dropping!‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	+0:20 sec: Autopilot and flight control reverts to Direct Mode. Pitch up attitude peaks at 18¬∞.
	‚Ä¢	+0:25 sec: Aircraft stalls at 186 ft AGL.
	‚Ä¢	+0:30 sec: Full aerodynamic stall; nose drops rapidly.
	‚Ä¢	+0:38 sec: Ground impact at 54¬∞ nose-down attitude, 174 knots.

‚∏ª

‚öôÔ∏è Contributing Factors
	‚Ä¢	Environmental Conditions:
	‚Ä¢	Torrential rain during pushback.
	‚Ä¢	Moisture intrusion into PRB-A connector (P/N: HLN8471) ‚Äî a known corrosion-risk component.
	‚Ä¢	Latent Maintenance Issue:
	‚Ä¢	Power transfer relay unit showed signs of thermal damage in a previous MEL deferral 2 weeks prior.
	‚Ä¢	No replacement had been conducted; aircraft was cleared under repetitive deferral.
	‚Ä¢	Design Oversight:
	‚Ä¢	Boeing 787 has no physical engine control backup (i.e., no direct mechanical linkage in FADEC loss scenario).
	‚Ä¢	Loss of power supply to both EEC channels resulted in engine ‚Äúfreeze‚Äù at ground idle instead of flameout.
	‚Ä¢	Flight Crew Response:
	‚Ä¢	Attempted engine relight sequence not completed before stall onset.
	‚Ä¢	Emergency power selector not activated ‚Äî possibly due to confusion from multiple ECAM warnings.

‚∏ª

‚úàÔ∏è  Immediate Safety Actions
	‚Ä¢	DGCA + EASA + FAA Emergency AD issued within 24 hours:
	‚Ä¢	Mandatory PRB-A moisture integrity inspection on all Boeing 787 aircraft.
	‚Ä¢	Temporary restriction on dispatch with MEL items related to power transfer systems.
	‚Ä¢	Boeing:
	‚Ä¢	Issued Service Bulletin SB-787-24-212 requiring replacement of PRB-A connectors with sealed versions.
	‚Ä¢	Exploring addition of dual-path power redundancy for FADEC systems.

‚∏ª

üß† Lessons Learned
	‚Ä¢	Over-reliance on electrical power distribution architecture without layered redundancy.
	‚Ä¢	Lack of crew procedural training for full engine rollback during takeoff in EEC dual failure scenarios.
	‚Ä¢	Need for improved environmental sealing in GPU/electrical handover units in monsoon zones.

‚∏ª

üïØÔ∏è Human Toll
	‚Ä¢	The loss of 243 onboard lives, including 12 crew and 18 infants, deeply impacted the aviation community.
	‚Ä¢	Final words captured on CVR: ‚ÄúWe lost everything ‚Äì no thrust!‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	One family of five was killed on the ground in a hospital ambulance struck by debris.

‚∏ª

üìÖ Timeline ‚Äì What‚Äôs Next?
	‚Ä¢	Aug 15, 2025: Release of FAA/Boeing electrical design audit report
	‚Ä¢	Sept 5, 2025: ICAO session on electrical-critical phase-of-flight risk mitigation
	‚Ä¢	Oct 2025: Mandated design retrofit across 787 fleet (rev. SB-787-24-219)

Everyone talking about 'i see no flaps deployed'.
Yes flaps are usually deployed upto 20% for takeoffs to help with lift, but mark my words when i say that the 787 dreamliner family have massive state of the art Rolls Royce Trent 1000 engines each producing upto 78.000lb at takeoff thrust and would have no problem climbing out with flaps up. Even 1 of those engines would keep the aircraft airborne at rotation speed. The issue is clearly a total loss of thrust at around 600ft that steadily brought the bird back down. 
The big question is why...

author: @sarathNN
content: It seems like the flight/engine couldn't achieve it's speed to lift by the time it had reached the end of the runway. There's no recall option in such a last moment and it would have happened. It seems the speed of the flight was not enough which pulled it down from climbing and hit on the building. If it was a plane area in front without any building, most probably they would have survived some how I believe. The dust at the end of the takeoff seems either they were almost out of the runway edges or something had happened in between to bring that much dust/smoke from the engine side but even the airline authority says they haven't utilized the full length of the runway, flight records show that they have backtraced and utilized the full length of the runway. Definitely there had some issues with the thrust being offered by the engines to get the proper lift. If they had realized it from the very beginning of the runway, they had options to cancel the takeoff but they are helpless if it had reached the almost the end of the runway. Only option in front of them is to continue only where they can't take a turn in such scenariosüòîüòî

author: @saramuthu6690
content:
Referring to a similar incident before. India incident to be verified but it looks like a catastrophic electrical failure on rotation. 




Flight: AI-171 | Aircraft: Boeing 787-8 | Date: June 25, 2025 | Route: Ahmedabad (VAAH) ‚Üí London Heathrow (EGLL)
Crash Site: ~1.2 km from VAAH Runway 23, post-V1 and rotation
Fatalities: 247 (243 onboard + 4 ground)
Survivors: 0 onboard survivors (alternate to original), 3 injured on ground

‚∏ª

üõ†Ô∏è  AAIB Preliminary Report Highlights

1. Primary Cause ‚Äì Electrical Power Transfer Interruption (PTI) During Rotation
	‚Ä¢	During transition from ground to airborne electrical configuration, the aircraft experienced a cascading dual-engine FADEC (Full Authority Digital Engine Control) failure.
	‚Ä¢	Root cause: Uncommanded bus transfer failure due to arcing in the main power relay box (PRB-A), traced to water ingress during pre-flight GPU disconnection in heavy rain.
	‚Ä¢	This led to loss of electronic engine control at rotation, resulting in both GEnx engines rolling back to ground idle within 4‚Äì5 seconds.

2. Flight Data Record Timeline
	‚Ä¢	+0:11 sec: Nose gear lifts off.
	‚Ä¢	+0:13 sec: Sudden engine rollback begins. Thrust reduces from 92% N1 to <27% within 3 seconds.
	‚Ä¢	+0:16 sec: Master caution + ENG FAIL L/R warnings. FO calls, ‚ÄúBoth engines dropping!‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	+0:20 sec: Autopilot and flight control reverts to Direct Mode. Pitch up attitude peaks at 18¬∞.
	‚Ä¢	+0:25 sec: Aircraft stalls at 186 ft AGL.
	‚Ä¢	+0:30 sec: Full aerodynamic stall; nose drops rapidly.
	‚Ä¢	+0:38 sec: Ground impact at 54¬∞ nose-down attitude, 174 knots.

‚∏ª

‚öôÔ∏è Contributing Factors
	‚Ä¢	Environmental Conditions:
	‚Ä¢	Torrential rain during pushback.
	‚Ä¢	Moisture intrusion into PRB-A connector (P/N: HLN8471) ‚Äî a known corrosion-risk component.
	‚Ä¢	Latent Maintenance Issue:
	‚Ä¢	Power transfer relay unit showed signs of thermal damage in a previous MEL deferral 2 weeks prior.
	‚Ä¢	No replacement had been conducted; aircraft was cleared under repetitive deferral.
	‚Ä¢	Design Oversight:
	‚Ä¢	Boeing 787 has no physical engine control backup (i.e., no direct mechanical linkage in FADEC loss scenario).
	‚Ä¢	Loss of power supply to both EEC channels resulted in engine ‚Äúfreeze‚Äù at ground idle instead of flameout.
	‚Ä¢	Flight Crew Response:
	‚Ä¢	Attempted engine relight sequence not completed before stall onset.
	‚Ä¢	Emergency power selector not activated ‚Äî possibly due to confusion from multiple ECAM warnings.

‚∏ª

‚úàÔ∏è  Immediate Safety Actions
	‚Ä¢	DGCA + EASA + FAA Emergency AD issued within 24 hours:
	‚Ä¢	Mandatory PRB-A moisture integrity inspection on all Boeing 787 aircraft.
	‚Ä¢	Temporary restriction on dispatch with MEL items related to power transfer systems.
	‚Ä¢	Boeing:
	‚Ä¢	Issued Service Bulletin SB-787-24-212 requiring replacement of PRB-A connectors with sealed versions.
	‚Ä¢	Exploring addition of dual-path power redundancy for FADEC systems.

‚∏ª

üß† Lessons Learned
	‚Ä¢	Over-reliance on electrical power distribution architecture without layered redundancy.
	‚Ä¢	Lack of crew procedural training for full engine rollback during takeoff in EEC dual failure scenarios.
	‚Ä¢	Need for improved environmental sealing in GPU/electrical handover units in monsoon zones.

‚∏ª

üïØÔ∏è Human Toll
	‚Ä¢	The loss of 243 onboard lives, including 12 crew and 18 infants, deeply impacted the aviation community.
	‚Ä¢	Final words captured on CVR: ‚ÄúWe lost everything ‚Äì no thrust!‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	One family of five was killed on the ground in a hospital ambulance struck by debris.

‚∏ª

üìÖ Timeline ‚Äì What‚Äôs Next?
	‚Ä¢	Aug 15, 2025: Release of FAA/Boeing electrical design audit report
	‚Ä¢	Sept 5, 2025: ICAO session on electrical-critical phase-of-flight risk mitigation
	‚Ä¢	Oct 2025: Mandated design retrofit across 787 fleet (rev. SB-787-24-219)

Dear Members of the Saint Peter‚Äôs University Community,

It is with deep sorrow that we share news of a heartbreaking tragedy that has touched one of our own. our student from the Data Science Institute at the Frank J. Guarini School of Business, has experienced an unfathomable loss, as her sister, along with her family of five, were among those aboard the Air India flight that tragically crashed on Thursday.

On behalf of the entire Saint Peter‚Äôs community, I extend our heartfelt condolences to our student and her loved ones. We mourn alongside her and hold her in our thoughts and prayers during this profoundly difficult time.

Guided by the Jesuit value of being men and women for and with others, we unite as a community in prayer, presence and support during this heartbreaking time. In that spirit,.................. director of the Center for Global Learning, and ................chair and director of the Data Science Institute, are working closely with our student to ensure she receives the care, support and resources she needs. I encourage any member of our community who may be affected by this tragedy to reach out for support through our counseling and campus ministry services.

Together, let us stand in solidarity with those who are grieving and may we honor the memory of the lives lost.

In peace and prayer,

author: @TommyTCGT
content: Electrical glitch and design..when electrical power is interrupted, even for a fraction of a second, 787 and 777, for any reason, the spring loaded fuel cutoff valves to the engines will snap shut. This design is that in case of electrical failure, which means fire extinguishers cannot be activated, fuel shuts off automatically so the wing does not burn through from an engine fire. At take off there seems to have been an electrical snag. Happened to ANA 787 after landing using reversers, in Tokyo, and unable to restart. Happened to BA 777 landed safely mile before runway in London

*@MaydayAirDisaster* This channel is the official YouTube channel for the popular documentary television series "Mayday: Air Disaster," also known as "Air Crash Investigation" in many parts of the world. This riveting series delves into some of history's most catastrophic aviation accidents, providing in-depth investigations into how and why these tragedies occurred. Through a combination of expert analysis, compelling reenactments, and sometimes even survivor testimonies, the channel aims to uncover the crucial lessons learned from each incident, ultimately contributing to making air travel safer.
Each episode on the channel meticulously reconstructs the sequence of events leading up to a disaster. This often involves utilizing computer-generated imagery (CGI), voice-actor readings of cockpit voice recorder (CVR) transcripts, and interviews with crash investigators, retired pilots, and aviation experts. The channel not only recounts the events of the crash but also explores the rigorous investigative process that follows, highlighting the often complex chain of errors, mechanical failures, or human factors that contribute to such devastating outcomes. By presenting these detailed analyses, "Mayday: Air Disaster" serves as both a captivating true-crime style show and an educational resource for understanding aviation safety.


*I fully recommend looking in to this if you are interested*

content: read that when electrical power is interrupted, even for a fraction of a second, 787 and 777, for any reason, the spring loaded fuel cutoff valves to the engines will snap shut. This design is that in case of electrical failure, which means fire extinguishers cannot be activated, fuel shuts off automatic‡∏ülly so the wing does not burn through from an engine fire. At take off there seems to have been an electrical snag. Happened to ANA 787 after landing using reversers, in Tokyo, and unable to restart. Happened to BA 777 landed safely mile before runway in London.  Rtd Airline Training Capt
